subject: Re: [Read_Alphabet] Re: keyboard map uploaded
msgSnippet: ... Speaking of which, I have uploaded what I believe to be a much better mapping of Quickscript to the files/Resources section.  It is a word document,
messageBody:
> It turns out that ligatures are not to be represented at the Unicode
> level. It is another layer's responsibility. The Unicode proposal
> should only include the Junior QS forms as Oliver Langan has proposed.

Speaking of which, I have uploaded what I believe to be a much better
mapping of Quickscript to the files/Resources section. It is a word
document, containing images of the 'standard' glyphs and their names,
as well as alternate glyphs which might represent the same mapping.

Another project which I am working on (albeit slowly, since I am
supposed to be on holiday :) is an almost complete determination of
what ligatures might be present in a senior form of quickscript.
Basically, for each letter I have determined which other letters it
might possibly connect to (based on whether it ends on the topline or
the baseline). That part was easy, but now I am using the dictionary
from the QSConverter program to find examples of the ligatures (since
some possible ligatures are probably not represented in English). It
is time consuming, but a suggested part of the unicode proposal
process. I am going to write a small program to make it faster, and
will post it here when I am done.

A quick example for the pip character: the first two columns should be
in the jerome or king plus font. Of course, they are NOT ligatured,
but could be in a real 'senior' font.
